History.Post-Spellplague:
In [[1385 DR]], the [[Spellplague]] destroyed the buildings and fields of the village, forcing the survivors to flee.{{Cite organized play/LFR/Shades of Blue Fire|7}} Only the shell and foundation of the Icespear House and the ruins of The Rose and Hammer remained as evidence of the town that was.{{Cite organized play/LFR/Shades of Blue Fire|15}}

Deadsnows still drew visitors however - rumors abounded in [[Sundabar]] that a powerful group of adventurers who had settled in the town, the [[Brotherhood of the Moon]], were unable to retrieve the majority of their collected treasure when the Spellplague struck. Treasure hunters scoured the area for hidden caches for decades afterwards.{{Cite organized play/LFR/Shades of Blue Fire|21}}

In the 15{{th}} century DR, an orc bandit named [[Histarack]] discovered the Brotherhood's treasures. He then spread rumors that a new pocket of active [[blue fire]] had erupted in the area to keep the scavengers away. However, the story only served to garner the attention of the [[Order of Blue Fire]] who sent envoys to investigate the town's ruins and reveal the hoax for what it was.{{Cite organized play/LFR/Shades of Blue Fire|4}}

By the late 1480s or 1490s DR the town had been revived and repopulated.

During the [[War of the Silver Marches]], Lord [[Delvon Icespear]] was killed without an heir, leaving the town leaderless for some time.
